The inconsistency in `Instant.parse(..)` between JVM and iOS/native targets was due to the JVM implementation delegating to `java.time.OffsetDateTime.parse` when using the default `ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET` format. This platform-specific implementation was more lenient (allowing optional seconds) than the common `DateTimeComponents` implementation used by other targets (which strictly requires seconds as per documentation) and also caused issues with omitted offset minutes in some cases.

I have removed the platform-specific delegation in `core/jvm/src/Instant.kt`. Now, `Instant.parse` on JVM uses the common `DateTimeComponents.Formats.ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET` implementation, ensuring consistency across all platforms. This makes the JVM implementation:
1.  Stricter regarding seconds (matching iOS and documentation).
2.  Consistent in handling optional offset minutes (e.g. `+03` works).

I verified the fix with a reproduction test case that confirmed strictness for seconds and support for omitted offset minutes.

I also cleaned up unused imports in `core/jvm/src/Instant.kt`.

### Changes
Deleted `core/common/test/InstantReproductionTest.kt` (temporary test file).
Modified `core/jvm/src/Instant.kt` to remove `java.time` delegation.

```kotlin
// core/jvm/src/Instant.kt

// Removed unused imports
import java.time.Instant as jtInstant
import java.time.Clock as jtClock

// ...

        public actual fun parse(input: CharSequence, format: DateTimeFormat<DateTimeComponents>): Instant =
            try {
                format.parse(input).toInstantUsingOffset()
            } catch (e: IllegalArgumentException) {
                throw DateTimeFormatException("Failed to parse an instant from '$input'", e)
            }

        @Deprecated("This overload is only kept for binary compatibility", level = DeprecationLevel.HIDDEN)
        public fun parse(isoString: String): Instant = parse(input = isoString)

        // Removed fixOffsetRepresentation helper function as it is no longer needed
```

